<cite>U.  Straccia (2001) "Reasoning within Fuzzy Description Logics", Volume 14, pages 137-166</cite>
<p class="media"><a href="/media/813/live-813-1948-jair.pdf">PDF</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href="/media/813/live-813-1946-jair.ps">PostScript</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href='http://dx.doi.org/10.1613/jair.813'>doi:10.1613/jair.813</a></p>
<p>Description Logics (DLs) are suitable, well-known, logics    for managing structured knowledge.  They allow reasoning about    individuals and well defined concepts, i.e., set of individuals with    common properties.  The experience in using DLs in applications has    shown that in many cases we would like to extend their capabilities.    In particular, their use in the context of Multimedia Information    Retrieval (MIR) leads to the convincement that such DLs should allow    the treatment of the inherent imprecision in multimedia object content    representation and retrieval.     <p>      In this paper we will present a fuzzy extension of ALC, combining    Zadeh's fuzzy logic with a classical DL. In particular, concepts    becomes fuzzy and, thus, reasoning about imprecise concepts is    supported.  We will define its syntax, its semantics, describe its    properties and present a constraint propagation calculus for reasoning    in it.</p>
