<cite>M.  L. Ginsberg (2001) "GIB: Imperfect Information in a Computationally Challenging Game", Volume 14, pages 303-358</cite>
<cite>Honorable Mention for the 2006 IJCAI-JAIR Best Paper Prize</cite><p class="media"><a href="/media/820/live-820-1957-jair.pdf">PDF</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href="/media/820/live-820-1955-jair.ps">PostScript</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href='http://dx.doi.org/10.1613/jair.820'>doi:10.1613/jair.820</a></p>
<p>This paper investigates the problems arising in the    construction of a program to play the game of contract bridge.  These    problems include both the difficulty of solving the game's perfect    information variant, and techniques needed to address the fact that    bridge is not, in fact, a perfect information game.  GIB, the program    being described, involves five separate technical advances: partition    search, the practical application of Monte Carlo techniques to    realistic problems, a focus on achievable sets to solve problems    inherent in the Monte Carlo approach, an extension of alpha-beta    pruning from total orders to arbitrary distributive lattices, and the    use of squeaky wheel optimization to find approximately optimal    solutions to cardplay problems. <p>    GIB is currently believed to be of approximately expert caliber, and    is currently the strongest computer bridge program in the world.</p>
